   =20
      Saudi banking
   =20
 =20
Investment banking is a business of building long-term relationships. Your =
job, as an investment banker, is to become close to the people who possess =
giant piles of money, in the hopes that one day they will do giant deals wi=
th their giant piles of money and give you some of it. If you are at the we=
ekly meeting of an investment-banking group and everyone is going around th=
e room talking about what they did last week, and someone says =E2=80=9CI d=
id a billion-dollar=C2=A0merger and earned an $8=C2=A0million fee for the b=
ank,=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9CI played Settlers of Catan with Mark Zuc=
kerberg,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0you win, because the expected value of proximity to =
a giant pile of money is so much higher than the value of an actual fee fro=
m a normal-sized pile of money.One result of this is that banks are always =
happy to give freebies to the possessors of giant piles of money. =E2=80=9C=
We=E2=80=99ll do this work for Facebook at no charge because the opportunit=
y there is so vast and we want them to owe us one.=E2=80=9DThe possessors o=
f giant piles of money are, often, smart. Also they got to possess all of t=
hat money because they like hanging on to their money.One obvious result he=
re is that if you happen to possess a giant pile of money you can get free =
or discounted investment-banking services pretty much forever. You do a mul=
tibillion-dollar acquisition, your banker comes to you with a bill, you loo=
k at her in disappointment and say =E2=80=9Ca bill? I thought we were frien=
ds,=E2=80=9D her heart skips with joy, she tears up the bill, she goes back=
 to her bosses and says =E2=80=9Cthe giant pile of money=C2=A0thinks we=E2=
=80=99re friends,=E2=80=9D her bosses congratulate her on her success in re=
lationship-building, everyone is happy, and they all salivate to think abou=
t how much money they=E2=80=99ll make on your=C2=A0next,=C2=A0really big de=
al. And then=C2=A0you do the next, really big deal, and you repeat this pro=
cess forever.I promise you will never stop seeing  these stories=C2=A0about=
 Saudi Arabia:The latest crop of Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s market newcomers is=
 proving just as frugal when it comes to paying investment bankers.Despite =
attracting $125 billion in orders from investors for an initial public offe=
ring of Saudi Telecom Co.=E2=80=99s internet-services unit, banks including=
 Morgan Stanley and HSBC Holdings Plc are set to share just about $12 milli=
on in fees, Arabian Internet and Communications Services Co., also known as=
 solutions by stc, said in its prospectus.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s just 1.3% of=
 the offering value, compared with an average of about 5% or more for IPOs =
in the U.S. or Europe. Morgan Stanley alone had a bigger payday during UiPa=
th Inc.=E2=80=99s $1.54 billion IPO in April, which generated a total of $6=
7 million in fees. ...IPO riches have yet to materialize for global banks d=
espite a bonanza of share sales this year. Wall Street heavyweights like JP=
Morgan Chase & Co., Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Citigroup Inc. have still =
flocked to the kingdom, hiring teams on the ground and sending in their top=
 executives to sway local officials in the hope of winning advisory roles.I=
f banks are flocking to you because you have so much money, you don=E2=80=
=99t have to give them any of it.
