<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Tax rules</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that a basic rule is that if y=
ou have devoted your professional life to corporate inversions, in which U.=
S. companies merge with companies in low-tax jurisdictions in order to redu=
ce their tax bills, you have devoted your life to=C2=A0<em>doing=C2=A0</em>=
the inversions. There=E2=80=99s money in that! A company comes to you and i=
s like =E2=80=9Cwe=C2=A0would like to pay lower taxes so we could have more=
 money,=E2=80=9D and you are like =E2=80=9Clet me spend months structuring =
a deal to make that happen,=E2=80=9D and you do and it works, and you send =
the company a large bill and they cheerfully pay it. You have rendered a va=
luable service and gotten paid for it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It i=
s less likely, if you have devoted your professional life to corporate inve=
rsions, that you have devoted your life to=C2=A0<em>stopping=C2=A0</em>the =
inversions. There is no money in that! A company comes to you and is like =
=E2=80=9Cwe would like to pay lower taxes so we could have more money,=E2=
=80=9D and you are like =E2=80=9Cno, that is unpatriotic, stay here,=E2=80=
=9D and the company is like =E2=80=9Chuh okay whatever=E2=80=9D and goes to=
 someone else.[1] You have rendered no service and gotten no money, and eve=
ntually you will have to find something else to do for work if you want to =
keep paying rent.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now of course there is a =
possible exception, which is government service. In theory you could work f=
or the Internal Revenue Service and have a career as an inversion-fighter. =
But it is unlikely for simple institutional-design reasons. If the IRS deci=
des as a policy =E2=80=9Cwe will fight every inversion,=E2=80=9D it won=E2=
=80=99t just go do that; it will write a=C2=A0<em>rule=C2=A0</em>saying =E2=
=80=9Cinversions are illegal=E2=80=9D or whatever. And then people will sto=
p doing them and start doing other tax structuring instead. Or more likely =
the IRS will write a rule saying =E2=80=9Cinversions like <em>this </em>are=
 legal, and inversions like <em>that </em>are illegal,=E2=80=9D and profess=
ional inversion-doers will focus on doing the legal kind of inversions and =
arguing that gray-area cases are more like the legal kind, and IRS employee=
s will be in the business not of=C2=A0<em>fighting inversions=C2=A0</em>but=
 of=C2=A0<em>evaluating which close calls are okay</em>. And they will appr=
ove some and fight others and maybe take an overall=C2=A0skeptical view but=
 not be knee-jerk inversion fighters.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also =
they won=E2=80=99t have that much <em>work</em>, because most of what the p=
rofessional inversion-doers do will be clearly legal inversions rather than=
 borderline cases, so the IRS won=E2=80=99t employ that many inversion-exam=
iners relative to the absolutely booming private-sector professional field =
of inversion-doers. The IRS inversion-examiners will be generalists who do =
inversion examining as one part of a larger portfolio of responsibilities, =
or they will be inversion specialists but there will be like two of them.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also of course the IRS will pay less than th=
e private sector but that=E2=80=99s not the main point. The main point is t=
hat doing creative complicated things to minimize the taxes that companies =
pay is a big industry because it generates a lot of money (in reduced taxes=
), but doing creative complicated things to <em>maximize </em>the taxes tha=
t companies pay is=C2=A0<em>not </em>a big industry with a lot of specialis=
ts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you are the IRS and you want =
to write some new rules about corporate inversions and you think to yoursel=
f =E2=80=9Cwe need to hire the world=E2=80=99s 10 leading experts in corpor=
ate inversions,=E2=80=9D every single one of them will have built a private=
-sector career helping corporations do inversions, and every single one of =
them, after a few years of government service, will go back to a private-se=
ctor career helping corporations do inversions,=C2=A0and when you ask them =
=E2=80=9Cwhat rules should we write about inversions=E2=80=9D they will say=
 =E2=80=9Cyou should write very=C2=A0<em>complicated=C2=A0</em>rules about =
inversions, because that will increase the value of my advice, but also you=
 should definitely write rules that=C2=A0<em>allow lots of inversions</em>,=
 because that will also=C2=A0increase the value of my advice.=E2=80=9D No, =
no. They will be much less cynical than that; they are good people who have=
, in a burst of public-spiritedness, accepted a job at the IRS writing new =
rules. But they have spent their lives doing inversions, and their natural =
tendency will be to=C2=A0<em>like inversions</em> and prefer rules that all=
ow for lots of them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25093534.264700/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cub=
nl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8wOS8xOS9idXNpbmVzcy9hY2NvdW50aW5nLWZpcm1zLXRheC1sb29w=
aG9sZXMtZ292ZXJubWVudC5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb0b465d4" itemprop=3D=
