</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A good empirical question in academic =
finance is: When investment bankers work for the target in a merger, do the=
y try to get a=C2=A0<em>high price=C2=A0</em>or a=C2=A0<em>low price?=C2=A0=
</em>The obvious answer is =E2=80=9Chigh price=E2=80=9D: The bankers work f=
or the target, they are negotiating against the acquirer, and the higher th=
e price they get the more they have won. They are repeat players in this bu=
siness,=C2=A0and when they go pitch=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>companies to r=
epresent them in mergers, they will want to show their negotiating credenti=
als by pointing to all the times they negotiated high prices.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a good contrarian argument for =E2=80=9Cl=
ow price.=E2=80=9D For one thing there are conflicts of interest: A banker =
who represents a target in one deal might represent an acquirer in the next=
, and big acquirers provide more repeat business than targets do; if you gi=
ve a private equity acquirer a good deal today they might hire you tomorrow=
. Also, though, if you are a sell-side M&amp;A banker, your main economic i=
ncentive is to=C2=A0<em>get a deal done:=C2=A0</em>You get paid=C2=A0<em>mo=
re=C2=A0</em>for getting a deal done at a higher price (generally), but you=
 get paid=C2=A0<em>nothing</em> if there=E2=80=99s no deal. So your job is =
not just to try to extract the highest possible price out of the acquirer; =
it is also to get your own client comfortable with a lower price, because y=
our main goal is to make a deal happen at=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>price.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is a paper titled=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25093534.264=
700/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTM=
3NzE2NjQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCfedce0fe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Peer Selection and Valuation in Mergers a=
nd Acquisitions</a>,=E2=80=9D by Gregory Eaton, Feng Guo, Tingting Liu and =
Micah Officer, on a related question:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Using unique data, this paper examines investment banks=E2=80=99 cho=
ice of peers in comparable companies analysis in mergers and acquisitions. =
We find strong evidence that product market space is amongst the most impor=
tant factors in peer selection, but we provide evidence indicating that Sta=
ndard Industrial Classification (SIC) codes, particularly three- and four-d=
igit codes, do a poor job of categorizing related firms in this setting. Ba=
nks strategically select large, high growth peers with high valuation multi=
ples, factors that are also positively related to premiums. Our evidence is=
 consistent with target-firm advisors selecting peers with high valuation m=
ultiples to negotiate higher takeover prices.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">How much is a company worth? Well, loosely speaking, it is =
worth (1) its annual earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amor=
tization=C2=A0<em>times=C2=A0</em>(2) the median enterprise-value-to-Ebitda=
 ratio of its peers.[5] So the way to value a company is to=C2=A0<em>pick a=
 list of peers</em>. If you pick a list of companies with high EV/Ebitda ra=
tios as =E2=80=9Cpeers,=E2=80=9D you will get a high valuation; if you pick=
 a list of companies with low multiples, you will get a low valuation:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That selection process is almost su=
rely driven by the target=E2=80=99s principal advisor in the M&amp;A transa=
ction, which is typically an investment bank or advisory firm. The true inc=
entives driving investment bankers=E2=80=99 peer selection are, of course, =
unobservable. However, in this paper we examine whether the characteristics=
 of peer firms chosen by target firms=E2=80=99 investment banks suggest tha=
t banks choose peers to aid in the negotiation of a higher offer price for =
target firm shareholders, or, conversely, choose peers that help with the c=
ompletion of a proposed deal. The latter of which enables the bank to colle=
ct their advisory fees, a large fraction of which are typically conditional=
 on deal completion. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The incentive to s=
elect peers in such a way that helps the target in negotiation with a prosp=
ective bidder would imply that the target=E2=80=99s investment bank chooses=
 peers that, all else equal, have higher valuation multiples, which make th=
e perceived value of the target firm appear higher. Conversely, the incenti=
ve to select peers in a way that helps with the closing of a transaction (a=
nd the bank=E2=80=99s collection of its advisory fees) would imply that the=
 investment bank chooses peers that, all else equal, have lower valuation m=
ultiples. This would make the bidder=E2=80=99s offer appear more generous t=
o target shareholders, increasing the probability that they accept the offe=
r. Because the investment bank advising the target firm in the transaction =
has significant discretion in the choice of peers,=C2=A0which of the incent=
ive effects dominates is an empirical question and is the main focus of our=
 study.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I actually think that,=
 if you=E2=80=99ve met investment bankers, it=E2=80=99s fairly clear that t=
he =E2=80=9Chigh price=E2=80=9D incentives would dominate and that sell-sid=
e bankers would pick high-valuation peers, and that is in fact the result t=
he authors get. (If you=E2=80=99re a banker you tend to view yourself as a =
master negotiator and put your effort into squeezing out a higher price; la=
ter, when you write the fairness opinion, you=E2=80=99ll regret all your bl=
uster about how valuable the company is, but that regret is not going to ch=
ange your behavior.) Also though bankers in management buyouts =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0where the target management is also the buyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0are more co=
nflicted and might choose lower multiples:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">We examine some additional incentive effects in the peer select=
ion process. Specifically,=C2=A0we examine whether the results described ab=
ove also hold in a sample of management buyout deals. Management buyouts pr=
esent a setting where concerns about agency problems are particularly germa=
ne because the target firm=E2=80=99s managers have the incentive to purchas=
e their firm from shareholders at the lowest possible price. Our results in=
 this subsample suggest that peers selected in buyout deals tend to have lo=
wer valuation ratios and weaker operating performance. However, these resul=
ts weaken once we control for bidder characteristics. Thus, although we are=
=C2=A0not able to reach a definitive conclusion, we provide some evidence t=
hat investment banks may strategically select low-value peers to justify th=
e lower premiums offered in buyout deals.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">A further possibility is that bankers use high-value peers when=
 negotiating the deal, and then low-value peers when writing the fairness o=
pinion to try to get the deal approved,=C2=A0but that seems a bit unsportin=
g.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0"=
 cellpadding=3D"0">
